{"title_page": "Michael Petry", "text_new": "{{for|the German footballer|Michael Petry (footballer)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Michael Petry\n| image = Michael Petry.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1960\n| birth_place = [[El Paso]], [[Texas]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American/British\n| website = www.michaelpetry.net\n| field = [[Conceptual Art]], [[Installation Art]], [[Queer Theory]]\n}}\n\n'''Michael Petry''' (born 1960) is an American multi-media artist and author who lives and works in [[London]]. He is director of MOCA, London (Museum of Contemporary Art London), and co-founder of the Museum of Installation, also in London. He was formerly the Curator of the [[Royal Academy Schools]] Gallery, Guest Curator at the KunstAkademi, [[Oslo]], and Research Fellow at the [[University of Wolverhampton]].\n\n==Life and work==\nPetry was born in [[El Paso]], [[Texas]], and has lived in [[London]] since 1981. Petry received a BA at [[Rice University]] (Houston), an MA at [[London Guildhall University]], and a Phd in Arts at [[Middlesex University]].\n\nHe is the Director of MOCA, London (the Museum of Contemporary Art) and a former curator of the [[Royal Academy Schools]] Gallery.\n\nIn 2009 Petry received a commission from [[The Ivy]] restaurant, London, to make a large scale glass installation called \"The Network\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westbrookgallery.com/gallery-artists/artwork/ivy-private-club-installation |title=Ivy Private club installation &#124; Westbrook Gallery - London - Contemporary &amp; Modern art Gallery |work=westbrookgallery.com |year=2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130209122026/http://www.westbrookgallery.com/gallery-artists/artwork/ivy-private-club-installation |archivedate=9 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Petry was chosen to be the first Artist in Residence at the [[Sir John Soane's Museum]], London<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708063319/http://www.soane.org/exhibitions/michael_petry_touching_the_neoclassical_and_romantic |title=Exhibitions \" Michael Petry: Touching the Neoclassical and Romantic |first= |last= |work=soane.org |year=2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Petry headlined Rice University's Campbell Lecture Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humanities.rice.edu/whats-happening/events/campbell-lecture-series/michael-petry|title=Michael Petry {{!}} Humanities|website=humanities.rice.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://humanities.rice.edu/whats-happening/events/campbell-lecture-series/michael-petry|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref> The program was entitled \"The Trouble with Michael: Artist and Rice Alumni Michael Petry Discusses His 30 Years of Art Production,\" and involved three lectures: \"Growing Up in Public\" (April 7, 2015), \"Reading a Life\" (April 8, 2015) and \"The Art of Ethics\" (April 9, 2015). A coinciding exhibition of Petry's work, ''At the Core of the Algorithm,'' was shown at Hiram Butler Gallery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hirambutler.com/exhibitions/view/michael-petry-at-the-core-of-the-algorithm|title=Michael Petry - AT the Core of the Algorithm {{!}} Hiram Butler Gallery|website=hirambutler.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413225222/http://hirambutler.com/exhibitions/view/michael-petry-at-the-core-of-the-algorithm|archivedate=2017-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Petry and Travis Barker entered a Civil Partnership at the London Borough of Southwark.\n\n[[Image:The Treasure of Memory 1.jpg|thumb|Petry's piece \"The Treasure of Memory\"]]\n\n==Books==\nPetry co-authored ''Installation Art'' ([[Thames & Hudson]], 1994), and ''Installation Art in the New Millennium'' (Thames & Hudson, 2003), and authored ''Abstract Eroticism'' (1996) and ''A Thing of Beauty is...'' ([[John Wiley & Sons|Academy Editions]], 1997). ''The Trouble with Michael'' (ArtMedia Press, 2001) is a monograph of his artistic practice.\n\nPetry's book ''Hidden Histories: 20th Century Same Sex Male Lovers in the Visual Arts'' (2004) accompanies the exhibition ''Hidden Histories'' he curated for [[The New Art Gallery Walsall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/hidden-histories|title=Hidden Histories  -  The New Art Gallery  Walsall|website=www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk|accessdate=20 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009022040/http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/hidden-histories|archivedate=9 October 2011}}</ref> He documented the exhibition in ''The International Journal of Art & Design Education'' and to expand this for publication in ''Gender Sexuality, and Museums: A Routledge Reader'' edited by Amy K. Levin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Gender-Sexuality-%20and-Museums-%20A-Routledge-%20Reader/Levin/p/book/9780415554923|title=Gender, Sexuality and Museums: A Routledge Reader (Paperback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://www.routledge.com/Gender-Sexuality-%20and-Museums-%20A-Routledge-%20Reader/Levin/p/book/9780415554923|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref>\n\nHis book ''Golden Rain Volumes I & II'' is part of his project of the same name for Ha gamle prestegard's exhibition ''On the Edge''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakanten.no/artikkel.aspx?MId1=4294&AId=3825&back=1|title=P\u00e5 Kanten|website=www.pakanten.no|accessdate=20 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303210155/http://www.pakanten.no/artikkel.aspx?MId1=4294&AId=3825&back=1|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> for [[Stavanger]] 2008, [[European Capital of Culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kunstkritikk.no/kritikk/kunst-pa-kanten/|title=Kunst p\u00e5 kanten|first=Trond|last=Borgen|website=Kunstkritikk|accessdate=20 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320233258/http://www.kunstkritikk.no/kritikk/kunst-pa-kanten/|archivedate=20 March 2012}}</ref> His work is included in the ''Contemporary Glass'' book by [[Black Dog Publishing]]. Petry's book ''The Art of Not Making: the new artist/artisan relationship'' (Thames & Hudson, 2011) looks at artists who have work produced for them by artisans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_9441000/9441988.stm|title=In pictures: Artful dodgers|date=5 April 2011|accessdate=20 January 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306162511/http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_9441000/9441988.stm|archivedate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPetry's 2013 book ''Nature Morte: Contemporary Artists Reinvigorate the Still Life Tradition'' (Thames & Hudson) revealed how leading artists of the 21st century are reinvigorating the still life, a genre previously synonymous with the 16th- and 17th-century Old Masters. ''Nature Morte'' was adapted into a touring exhibition which visited several European galleries and museums.\n\nHe has also contributed chapters to various books and journals, including ''Pornographic Art and the Aesthetics of Pornography'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2013),<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9780230368200#aboutAuthors|title=Pornographic Art and the Aesthetics of Pornography {{!}} H. Maes {{!}} Palgrave Macmillan|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629112305/http://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9780230368200#aboutAuthors|archivedate=2017-06-29}}</ref> ''Sculpture and Touch'' (Routledge, 2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Sculpture-and-%20Touch/Dent/p/book/9781409412311|title=Sculpture and Touch (Hardback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://www.routledge.com/Sculpture-and-%20Touch/Dent/p/book/9781409412311|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref> and ''Global Mobilities: Refugees, Exiles and Immigrants in Museums and Archives'' (Routledge, 2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Global-Mobilities-%20Refugees-Exiles-%20and-Immigrants-%20in-Museums-%20and-Archives/Levin/p/book/9781138906327|title=Global Mobilities: Refugees, Exiles, and Immigrants in Museums and Archives (Hardback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://www.routledge.com/Global-Mobilities-%20Refugees-Exiles-%20and-Immigrants-%20in-Museums-%20and-Archives/Levin/p/book/9781138906327|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn Petry's 2018 book, ''The Word is Art'' (Thames & Hudson) he asserts the value of text in art by examining the use of text by artists from around the world, including Bruce Nauman, Julien Breton, Jeremy Deller, Takashi Murakami, Tracey Emin, Christian Boltanski, Joe Ovelman, Jenny Holzer, Ed Ruscha, Glenn Ligon and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/art-photography/article/41806/1/word-is-art-book-thames-hudson-text-jenny-holzer-barbara-kruger-glenn-ligon|title=This book features the world\u2019s most riveting word artworks|last=Dazed|date=2018-11-12|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nPetry also writes regularly for ''The Huffington Post.''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/dr-michael-petry/|title=Dr Michael Petry|website=HuffPost UK|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612043022/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/dr-michael-petry|archivedate=2017-06-12}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* ''Laughing at Time'', Ha gamle prestegard, Norway, 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.no/event/laughing-at-%20time-michael-%20petry|title=Listen|website=Listen|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://listen.no/event/laughing-at-%20time-michael-%20petry|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref>\n* ''America the Beautiful'', Sundaram Tagore Gallery, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaramtagore.com/exhibitions/michael-petry2|title=Michael Petry - Exhibitions - Sundaram Tagore Gallery|website=www.sundaramtagore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228183030/http://www.sundaramtagore.com/exhibitions/michael-petry2|archivedate=2017-12-28}}</ref>\n* ''Glasswear'', Museum of Arts and Design, New York, 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mad.emuseum.com/exhibitions/417/glasswear/objects|title=Works \u2013 GlassWear \u2013 Exhibitions \u2013 eMuseum|website=mad.emuseum.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019084700/http://mad.emuseum.com/exhibitions/417/glasswear/objects|archivedate=2017-10-19}}</ref>\n* ''[[Glasstress]] II'', 54th [[Venice Biennale]], Venice, Italy, 2011.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n* ''Michael Petry: The Touch of the Oracle,'' [[Palm Springs Art Museum]], Palm Springs, CA, 2012.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n* ''AT the Core of the Algorithm'', installation for British Glass, Glazenhuis, Lommel, Belgium, 2014<ref>{{Citation|last=Gallery|first=Hiram Butler|title=Michael Petry: AT the Core of the Algorithm|date=2014-12-06|url=https://vimeo.com/113793860|accessdate=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130054024/https://vimeo.com/113793860|archivedate=2016-01-30}}</ref>\n* ''Frontiers Reimagined'', Museo di Palazzo Grimani, Official Collateral Event as part of the 56th International Art Exhibition of la Biennale di Venezia, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaramtagore.com/publications/frontiers-reimagined|title=Frontiers Reimagined - Publications - Sundaram Tagore Gallery|website=www.sundaramtagore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928185926/http://www.sundaramtagore.com/publications/frontiers-reimagined|archivedate=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n* ''A Twist in Time'', solo exhibition at [[Pallant House Gallery]], 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pallant.org.uk/about1/press-office/press-releases/2015/michael-petry-a-twist-in-time|title=Pallant House Gallery|website=www.pallant.org.uk|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408155035/http://www.pallant.org.uk/about1/press-office/press-releases/2015/michael-petry-a-twist-in-time|archivedate=2016-04-08}}</ref>\n* ''At The Foot of the Gods'', installation for the Bi\u00ebnnale Oosterhou, Holland, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kunstindeheiligedriehoek.nl/Uploads/Editor/Download%20het%20Persbericht.pdf|title=Bi\u00ebnnale Oosterhou, Holland 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://kunstindeheiligedriehoek.nl/Uploads/Editor/Download%20het%20Persbericht.pdf|archive-date=2018-01-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''The WORD'', an exhibition curated by Petry for Helsinki Contemporary, Helsinki, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://helsinkicontemporary.com/exhibition/the-book-%20of-the-%20word|title=Ville Andersson: I can't go on. I will go on.|last=Contemporary|first=Helsinki|website=helsinkicontemporary.com|language=fi-FI|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n* ''In the Realm of the Gods'', an exhibition at the [[Holburne Museum]], Bath, 2017\u20132018<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.holburne.org/events/michael-petry-in-the-realm-of-the-gods/|title=Michael Petry: In the Realm of the Gods|work=The Holburne Museum|access-date=2018-01-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== The Art of Not Making ===\nPetry's book ''The Art of Not Making: The New Artist/Artisan Relationship'' was adapted into a series of exhibitions which Petry curated: ''The Fabricated Object'', Sumarria Lunn Gallery,  London, 2012; ''The Art of Not Making'', Ha gamle prestegard, Norway, 2013.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n=== Nature Morte ===\n''Nature Morte: Contemporary Artists Reinvigorate the Still Life Tradition,'' Petry's 2013 book was adapted into a touring exhibition which was presented at Ha gamle prestegard, Norway, 2015; Konsthallen-Bohusl\u00e4ns Museum, Sweden, 2016; [[National Museum, Wroc\u0142aw]], Poland, 2017; [[Guildhall Art Gallery|The Guildhall Art Gallery]], London, 2017\u201318.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Collections==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\nPetry's work is held in the following public collections:\n*[[Museum of Arts and Design]], New York City\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]]\n*[[Toledo Museum of Art]]\n*[[British Museum]], London\n*The National Collection, UK\n*[[Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle der Bundesrepublik Deutschland]], [[Bonn]], Germany\n*Bellerive Museum, [[Zurich]]\n*[[The New Art Gallery Walsall]], UK\n*Rogaland Kunstmuseum, [[Stavanger]], Norway\n*The Gallery of Art, [[Legnica]], Poland\n*Leopold Hoesch Museum, [[D\u00fcren]], Germany\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sundaramtagore.com/artists/michael-petry/ Petry's page at Sundaram Tagor Gallery]\n* [http://www.dbhbg.com/michaelpetry.html Petry's page at Devin Borden Hiram Butler Gallery]\n* [http://bak.spc.org/everything/e/hard/text/moi.html Interview with Petry] by Steve Rushton, 'everything', 1994\n* [http://thefineartsociety.com/artists/34-michael-petry/overview/ Petry's page at The Fine Art Society]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petry, Michael}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Alumni of London Guildhall University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Middlesex University]]\n[[Category:Rice University alumni]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the German footballer|Michael Petry (footballer)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Michael Petry\n| image = Michael Petry.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1960\n| birth_place = [[El Paso]], [[Texas]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = American/British\n| website = www.michaelpetry.net\n| field = [[Conceptual Art]], [[Installation Art]], [[Queer Theory]]\n}}\n\n'''Michael Petry''' (born 1960) is an American multi-media artist and author who lives and works in [[London]]. He is director of MOCA, London (Museum of Contemporary Art London), and co-founder of the Museum of Installation, also in London. He was formerly the Curator of the [[Royal Academy Schools]] Gallery, Guest Curator at the KunstAkademi, [[Oslo]], and Research Fellow at the [[University of Wolverhampton]].\n\n==Life and work==\nPetry was born in [[El Paso]], [[Texas]], and has lived in [[London]] since 1981. Petry received a BA at [[Rice University]] (Houston), an MA at [[London Guildhall University]], and a Phd in Arts at [[Middlesex University]].\n\nHe is the Director of MOCA, London (the Museum of Contemporary Art) and a former curator of the [[Royal Academy Schools]] Gallery.\n\nIn 2009 Petry received a commission from [[The Ivy]] restaurant, London, to make a large scale glass installation called \"The Network\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westbrookgallery.com/gallery-artists/artwork/ivy-private-club-installation |title=Ivy Private club installation &#124; Westbrook Gallery - London - Contemporary &amp; Modern art Gallery |work=westbrookgallery.com |year=2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130209122026/http://www.westbrookgallery.com/gallery-artists/artwork/ivy-private-club-installation |archivedate=9 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Petry was chosen to be the first Artist in Residence at the [[Sir John Soane's Museum]], London<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708063319/http://www.soane.org/exhibitions/michael_petry_touching_the_neoclassical_and_romantic |title=Exhibitions \" Michael Petry: Touching the Neoclassical and Romantic |first= |last= |work=soane.org |year=2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Petry headlined Rice University's Campbell Lecture Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humanities.rice.edu/whats-happening/events/campbell-lecture-series/michael-petry|title=Michael Petry {{!}} Humanities|website=humanities.rice.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://humanities.rice.edu/whats-happening/events/campbell-lecture-series/michael-petry|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref> The program was entitled \"The Trouble with Michael: Artist and Rice Alumni Michael Petry Discusses His 30 Years of Art Production,\" and involved three lectures: \"Growing Up in Public\" (April 7, 2015), \"Reading a Life\" (April 8, 2015) and \"The Art of Ethics\" (April 9, 2015). A coinciding exhibition of Petry's work, ''At the Core of the Algorithm,'' was shown at Hiram Butler Gallery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hirambutler.com/exhibitions/view/michael-petry-at-the-core-of-the-algorithm|title=Michael Petry - AT the Core of the Algorithm {{!}} Hiram Butler Gallery|website=hirambutler.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413225222/http://hirambutler.com/exhibitions/view/michael-petry-at-the-core-of-the-algorithm|archivedate=2017-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Petry and Travis Barker entered a Civil Partnership at the London Borough of Southwark.\n\n[[Image:The Treasure of Memory 1.jpg|thumb|Petry's piece \"The Treasure of Memory\"]]\n\n==Books==\nPetry co-authored ''Installation Art'' ([[Thames & Hudson]], 1994), and ''Installation Art in the New Millennium'' (Thames & Hudson, 2003), and authored ''Abstract Eroticism'' (1996) and ''A Thing of Beauty is...'' ([[John Wiley & Sons|Academy Editions]], 1997). ''The Trouble with Michael'' (ArtMedia Press, 2001) is a monograph of his artistic practice.\n\nPetry's book ''Hidden Histories: 20th Century Same Sex Male Lovers in the Visual Arts'' (2004) accompanies the exhibition ''Hidden Histories'' he curated for [[The New Art Gallery Walsall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/hidden-histories|title=Hidden Histories  -  The New Art Gallery  Walsall|website=www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk|accessdate=20 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009022040/http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/hidden-histories|archivedate=9 October 2011}}</ref> He documented the exhibition in ''The International Journal of Art & Design Education'' and to expand this for publication in ''Gender Sexuality, and Museums: A Routledge Reader'' edited by Amy K. Levin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Gender-Sexuality-%20and-Museums-%20A-Routledge-%20Reader/Levin/p/book/9780415554923|title=Gender, Sexuality and Museums: A Routledge Reader (Paperback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://www.routledge.com/Gender-Sexuality-%20and-Museums-%20A-Routledge-%20Reader/Levin/p/book/9780415554923|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref>\n\nHis book ''Golden Rain Volumes I & II'' is part of his project of the same name for Ha gamle prestegard's exhibition ''On the Edge''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakanten.no/artikkel.aspx?MId1=4294&AId=3825&back=1|title=P\u00e5 Kanten|website=www.pakanten.no|accessdate=20 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303210155/http://www.pakanten.no/artikkel.aspx?MId1=4294&AId=3825&back=1|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> for [[Stavanger]] 2008, [[European Capital of Culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kunstkritikk.no/kritikk/kunst-pa-kanten/|title=Kunst p\u00e5 kanten|first=Trond|last=Borgen|website=Kunstkritikk|accessdate=20 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320233258/http://www.kunstkritikk.no/kritikk/kunst-pa-kanten/|archivedate=20 March 2012}}</ref> His work is included in the ''Contemporary Glass'' book by [[Black Dog Publishing]]. Petry's book ''The Art of Not Making: the new artist/artisan relationship'' (Thames & Hudson, 2011) looks at artists who have work produced for them by artisans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_9441000/9441988.stm|title=In pictures: Artful dodgers|date=5 April 2011|accessdate=20 January 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306162511/http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_9441000/9441988.stm|archivedate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPetry's 2013 book ''Nature Morte: Contemporary Artists Reinvigorate the Still Life Tradition'' (Thames & Hudson) revealed how leading artists of the 21st century are reinvigorating the still life, a genre previously synonymous with the 16th- and 17th-century Old Masters. ''Nature Morte'' was adapted into a touring exhibition which visited several European galleries and museums.\n\nHe has also contributed chapters to various books and journals, including ''Pornographic Art and the Aesthetics of Pornography'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2013),<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9780230368200#aboutAuthors|title=Pornographic Art and the Aesthetics of Pornography {{!}} H. Maes {{!}} Palgrave Macmillan|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629112305/http://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9780230368200#aboutAuthors|archivedate=2017-06-29}}</ref> ''Sculpture and Touch'' (Routledge, 2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Sculpture-and-%20Touch/Dent/p/book/9781409412311|title=Sculpture and Touch (Hardback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://www.routledge.com/Sculpture-and-%20Touch/Dent/p/book/9781409412311|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref> and ''Global Mobilities: Refugees, Exiles and Immigrants in Museums and Archives'' (Routledge, 2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Global-Mobilities-%20Refugees-Exiles-%20and-Immigrants-%20in-Museums-%20and-Archives/Levin/p/book/9781138906327|title=Global Mobilities: Refugees, Exiles, and Immigrants in Museums and Archives (Hardback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://www.routledge.com/Global-Mobilities-%20Refugees-Exiles-%20and-Immigrants-%20in-Museums-%20and-Archives/Levin/p/book/9781138906327|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn Petry's 2018 book, ''The Word is Art'' (Thames & Hudson) he asserts the value of text in art by examining the use of text by artists around the world, including Bruce Nauman, Julien Breton, Jeremy Deller, Takashi Murakami, Tracey Emin, Christian Boltanski, Joe Ovelman, Jenny Holzer, Ed Ruscha, Glenn Ligon and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/art-photography/article/41806/1/word-is-art-book-thames-hudson-text-jenny-holzer-barbara-kruger-glenn-ligon|title=This book features the world\u2019s most riveting word artworks|last=Dazed|date=2018-11-12|website=Dazed|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nPetry also writes regularly for ''The Huffington Post.''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/dr-michael-petry/|title=Dr Michael Petry|website=HuffPost UK|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612043022/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/dr-michael-petry|archivedate=2017-06-12}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* ''Laughing at Time'', Ha gamle prestegard, Norway, 2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.no/event/laughing-at-%20time-michael-%20petry|title=Listen|website=Listen|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://listen.no/event/laughing-at-%20time-michael-%20petry|archivedate=2018-01-20}}</ref>\n* ''America the Beautiful'', Sundaram Tagore Gallery, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaramtagore.com/exhibitions/michael-petry2|title=Michael Petry - Exhibitions - Sundaram Tagore Gallery|website=www.sundaramtagore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228183030/http://www.sundaramtagore.com/exhibitions/michael-petry2|archivedate=2017-12-28}}</ref>\n* ''Glasswear'', Museum of Arts and Design, New York, 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mad.emuseum.com/exhibitions/417/glasswear/objects|title=Works \u2013 GlassWear \u2013 Exhibitions \u2013 eMuseum|website=mad.emuseum.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019084700/http://mad.emuseum.com/exhibitions/417/glasswear/objects|archivedate=2017-10-19}}</ref>\n* ''[[Glasstress]] II'', 54th [[Venice Biennale]], Venice, Italy, 2011.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n* ''Michael Petry: The Touch of the Oracle,'' [[Palm Springs Art Museum]], Palm Springs, CA, 2012.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n* ''AT the Core of the Algorithm'', installation for British Glass, Glazenhuis, Lommel, Belgium, 2014<ref>{{Citation|last=Gallery|first=Hiram Butler|title=Michael Petry: AT the Core of the Algorithm|date=2014-12-06|url=https://vimeo.com/113793860|accessdate=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130054024/https://vimeo.com/113793860|archivedate=2016-01-30}}</ref>\n* ''Frontiers Reimagined'', Museo di Palazzo Grimani, Official Collateral Event as part of the 56th International Art Exhibition of la Biennale di Venezia, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaramtagore.com/publications/frontiers-reimagined|title=Frontiers Reimagined - Publications - Sundaram Tagore Gallery|website=www.sundaramtagore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928185926/http://www.sundaramtagore.com/publications/frontiers-reimagined|archivedate=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n* ''A Twist in Time'', solo exhibition at [[Pallant House Gallery]], 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pallant.org.uk/about1/press-office/press-releases/2015/michael-petry-a-twist-in-time|title=Pallant House Gallery|website=www.pallant.org.uk|access-date=2018-01-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408155035/http://www.pallant.org.uk/about1/press-office/press-releases/2015/michael-petry-a-twist-in-time|archivedate=2016-04-08}}</ref>\n* ''At The Foot of the Gods'', installation for the Bi\u00ebnnale Oosterhou, Holland, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kunstindeheiligedriehoek.nl/Uploads/Editor/Download%20het%20Persbericht.pdf|title=Bi\u00ebnnale Oosterhou, Holland 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120154047/https://kunstindeheiligedriehoek.nl/Uploads/Editor/Download%20het%20Persbericht.pdf|archive-date=2018-01-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''The WORD'', an exhibition curated by Petry for Helsinki Contemporary, Helsinki, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://helsinkicontemporary.com/exhibition/the-book-%20of-the-%20word|title=Ville Andersson: I can't go on. I will go on.|last=Contemporary|first=Helsinki|website=helsinkicontemporary.com|language=fi-FI|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n* ''In the Realm of the Gods'', an exhibition at the [[Holburne Museum]], Bath, 2017\u20132018<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.holburne.org/events/michael-petry-in-the-realm-of-the-gods/|title=Michael Petry: In the Realm of the Gods|work=The Holburne Museum|access-date=2018-01-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== The Art of Not Making ===\nPetry's book ''The Art of Not Making: The New Artist/Artisan Relationship'' was adapted into a series of exhibitions which Petry curated: ''The Fabricated Object'', Sumarria Lunn Gallery,  London, 2012; ''The Art of Not Making'', Ha gamle prestegard, Norway, 2013.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n=== Nature Morte ===\n''Nature Morte: Contemporary Artists Reinvigorate the Still Life Tradition,'' Petry's 2013 book was adapted into a touring exhibition which was presented at Ha gamle prestegard, Norway, 2015; Konsthallen-Bohusl\u00e4ns Museum, Sweden, 2016; [[National Museum, Wroc\u0142aw]], Poland, 2017; [[Guildhall Art Gallery|The Guildhall Art Gallery]], London, 2017\u201318.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Collections==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\nPetry's work is held in the following public collections:\n*[[Museum of Arts and Design]], New York City\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]]\n*[[Toledo Museum of Art]]\n*[[British Museum]], London\n*The National Collection, UK\n*[[Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle der Bundesrepublik Deutschland]], [[Bonn]], Germany\n*Bellerive Museum, [[Zurich]]\n*[[The New Art Gallery Walsall]], UK\n*Rogaland Kunstmuseum, [[Stavanger]], Norway\n*The Gallery of Art, [[Legnica]], Poland\n*Leopold Hoesch Museum, [[D\u00fcren]], Germany\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sundaramtagore.com/artists/michael-petry/ Petry's page at Sundaram Tagor Gallery]\n* [http://www.dbhbg.com/michaelpetry.html Petry's page at Devin Borden Hiram Butler Gallery]\n* [http://bak.spc.org/everything/e/hard/text/moi.html Interview with Petry] by Steve Rushton, 'everything', 1994\n* [http://thefineartsociety.com/artists/34-michael-petry/overview/ Petry's page at The Fine Art Society]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petry, Michael}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Alumni of London Guildhall University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Middlesex University]]\n[[Category:Rice University alumni]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citize